Panchaloha (Sanskrit: पञ्चलोह; Tamil: பஞ்சலோகம், ஐம்பொன்), also called Panchaloha (malayalam: പഞ്ചലോഹം) or Panchadhatu or Panchdhatu (Sanskrit: पञ्चधातु, lit. five metals) is a term for traditional five-metal alloys of sacred significance, used for making Hindu temple murtis and jewelry. The method for making Panchaloha images was a well-kept secret for a long period.
